We happen to choose this place because it is right next to the NY Department of State office in William St. They advertised 2 main dishes and 4 side dishes for $9.99 with free miso soup. That seems to be reasonably priced for Downtown NYC. I chose the teriyaki salmon. But they charged an extra $1 for it. The shredded beef was an extra 50 cents. The miso soup came in a 6 oz Styrofoam cup and was luke warm. The side of white rice was included among the 4 side dishes. Overall, food is good but I would not go back.

online Benton says they're open Saturday 11am-8pm. nowhere outside does it say they close at 7. went in at 7:15, no food displayed. got on the phone with wife discussing option, the attendant told me to hurry, kitchen closes at 7:30. so I asked if I could order rice, miso soup, udon and shumai (all things that only need to be heated in microwave) waited 15 minutes and asked her colleague why is the rice shumai, miso soup and udon taking so long. the colleague said the original attendant didn't charge me for rice (restaurant-speak for "not lisetening to your order". why it taking so long, because they are closed and making special consideration  for me. left the restaurant at 7:50 feeling special. the staff at Benton don't give a flying Fudge . better, efficient, polite, pleasant service at Burger King around corner.

As the name implies, this place specializes in bento boxes.  At BentOn, this means a box where you get to choose two "main" dishes and four "side" dishes. The two main dishes are almost always protein, and they generally have about four to six of these, of which you can choose two.  The selection varies from day to day, but is always made fresh daily, and ranges from teriyaki chicken or salmon to baked tofu to breaded fish. They have an even wider selection of side dishes.  The side dishes range from simple steamed vegetables to combination vegetable and protein salads.  Even though one gets four choices, I always have a difficult time, because so many of the dishes look so delicious. And all of this costs a little more than $10.00 per box.  I am often able to make more than one meal out of this because it can be do filling. In the past, I have also bought very good bibimbap, but I can't remember if that was on the menu the last time that I was there. Recently, they added a separate counter that specializes in just ramen, but I have not had a chance to check it out.

Great addition to the area! We had the Kagoshima tonkotsu ramen with egg and the Sakurajima spicy tonkotsu ramen with egg. I enjoyed the spicy broth as  it had a kick, a touch of sweetness, and a bit of smokiness, but my partner preferred  the simple, clean richness of the Kagoshima. The egg was almost hard-boiled, but still tasty. The staff was friendly and helpful. We will try the premium tonkotsu version next time - and hope the menu will expand to have more add-ins. The ramen holds its own against the Ippudos and Tottos of the city. There was no wait, though the seating area was almost full. The atmosphere is very casual.

This is a good spot for some Japanese and Korean quick lunch. They have ramen, bento boxes, bibimbop and curry dishes as well as some Japanese pastries.  The bibimbop is great because it has an egg, lots of vegetable and meat selection to choose from. It is more on the pricey side though for lunch. It comes to a little over $10 for bibimbop. In addition, I do like their mapo tofu over rice and it is really filling.  In short, this is a convenient and decent place for business lunch. It is definitely not very authentic but good enough for FiDi.
